<ns0:entry xmlns:ns0="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:ns1="http://schemas.google.com/g/2005" xmlns:ns2="http://schemas.google.com/projecthosting/issues/2009" ns1:etag="W/&quot;CEENRn47eCl7ImA9WhRaE04.&quot;">
		<ns0:id>http://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/full/1941</ns0:id><ns0:author>
			<ns0:name>dsch...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/104270846665912603141/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">Currently pnacl-ld passes both the -std-compile-opts and -O3 flags to opt when it performs LTO. This is redundant, as they use the same module-level passes. However, removing one of them causes 2 different failures on ARM. One of them (bugpoint-reduced bitcode attached) causes llc to generate an invalid Selection DAG and fail an assertion which requires only one glue input and output per DAG node. This DAG-glue code was under recent development at the time of our fork, and this bitcode does not cause crashes in the latest versions of LLVM, so after we merge closer to LLVM tip, we will revisit this issue.
